## 3 Carat Diamond Price by Color Grade

At 3 carats, the face-up diameter is 9.3mm — large enough that color becomes visible in ways it isn't at 1 carat. H and I color stones can show warmth in daylight under a white gold or platinum setting. Color selection matters more at 3ct than at any other size.

### D Color 3 Carat Round Diamond Price

D is the highest color grade — perfectly colorless by GIA definition. A [3ct D-VS2 GIA Excellent costs $72,930](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/25308687?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). That's a $24,000 premium over G-VS2 for a color difference no observer can see without a comparison stone under controlled lighting.

D color at 3ct makes sense in two situations: you're buying for investment-grade resale, or budget is completely unconstrained. For everyone else, D is overpaying.

### E–F Color 3 Carat Round Diamond Price

E and F hit the sweet spot — colorless appearance without the D premium. A [3ct E-VS2 GIA Excellent costs $60,880](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28416523?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational), saving $12,000 over a comparable D. A [3ct F-VS1 runs $65,650](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29207723?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational).

Both E and F are indistinguishable from D to the naked eye. If you want to truthfully say your diamond is colorless, E or F is the right grade.

### G Color 3 Carat Round Diamond Price

G at 3 carats reads as white to virtually everyone. The entry is [G-VVS1 at $44,500](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29113860?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) and [G-VS2 at $48,780](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/24964101?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). These are the two best-value natural 3ct options in the current market.

If someone tells you a G-color 3ct round looks yellow, they're either comparing it under UV lighting or they're wrong. In any real-world setting, G looks identical to D.

### H–I Color at 3 Carats

Avoid H and I color for 3ct rounds in platinum or white gold settings. At 9.3mm face-up, the slight warmth of H–I can show through — especially in natural daylight. In yellow gold, H–I is fine and saves $8,000–$15,000 over G equivalents.

---

## The Clarity Ceiling

There's a point where paying for better clarity stops improving anything you can see. At 3 carats, that ceiling is VS2.

A [3ct G-VS2 at $48,780](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/24964101?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) and a [3ct G-VVS1 at $44,500](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29113860?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) look identical face-up. You can only see the difference under 10× magnification. The extra cost of stepping from VS2 into VVS territory buys a better number on a certificate — nothing visible in the diamond.

The Clarity Ceiling is the grade at which paying more for clarity stops returning visible value. At 1 carat the ceiling is around SI1. At 3 carats, it moves up to VS2 — because the larger face-up area makes SI1 riskier to buy sight-unseen, and VS2 is the highest grade you actually need. VVS and FL grades at 3ct are purely certificate grades.

The one exception is investment buying. D-VVS or D-FL naturals are the only 3ct grades with meaningful secondary market demand. If you're buying to resell, those grades matter. If you're buying to wear, stop at VS2.

### 3 Carat VVS1 Diamond Price

At G color, VVS1 starts at [$44,500](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29113860?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). At F color, VVS1 reaches [$84,710](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29017695?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). That $40,000 spread is driven entirely by color, not clarity. It tells you how much color matters vs. clarity at this size.

### 3 Carat VS1–VS2 Clarity Price

VS2 is the clarity floor I recommend for 3ct rounds. The [3ct G-VS2 at $48,780](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/24964101?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is reliably eye-clean with no video review required. VS1 costs $5,000–$8,000 more for no visible improvement — but if VS2 inventory is thin when you're shopping, VS1 is a fine alternative.

### 3 Carat SI1 Round Diamond Price

SI1 at 3 carats requires individual vetting. Some SI1 stones are perfectly eye-clean at 9.3mm. Others have inclusions visible to the naked eye near the table. Always request HD video from Blue Nile before purchasing any 3ct SI1 — the price savings can be $8,000–$15,000, but you must check the specific stone. SI2 at 3ct: avoid entirely.

---

## 3 Carat D Flawless Diamond Price

D Flawless is the absolute ceiling of the GIA grading scale. At 3 carats in natural diamonds, D-FL stones are genuinely rare in standard retail — most trade through private dealers and auction houses at prices starting around **$90,000–$120,000+**.

In our Blue Nile dataset, [F-VVS1 at $84,710](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29017695?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the highest-grade stone captured. True 3ct D-FL naturals with GIA Excellent cut are collected and traded by high-end buyers who understand the market. They are not a practical purchase for most people.

Lab-grown is a different story. A [3ct IGI D-FL Ideal at $11,770](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28637534?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) gives you the same certificate grade for a fraction of the natural price. A [GIA-certified lab 3ct D-FL Excellent at $27,700](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29357218?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) still costs less than a natural G-VS2.

D-FL matters for natural stones bought as a genuine investment or heirloom. For wear and beauty, the [G-VS2 GIA Excellent at $48,780](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/24964101?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) looks identical face-up.

