The real comparison: [GIA natural 3ct G-VVS1 Excellent at $44,500](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29113860?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) vs [IGI lab 3ct D-VVS1 Ideal at $7,000](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29116878?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). The lab stone has a better color grade (D vs G) and equivalent optical performance — for $37,500 less.

No jeweler, gemologist, or friend at the table can tell them apart without a spectrometer.

![3 carat lab vs natural round diamond price savings — $5,800 lab vs $44,500 natural at equivalent size](/images/3ct-lab-vs-natural-round-diamond-savings.avif)

> **Farzana says:** "I tell every client the same thing: if you want the 3ct look for everyday wear, buy lab. The $37,500 you save buys a honeymoon, a down payment, or a second ring. The only real reason to buy natural at 3 carats is if you genuinely value rarity and origin — and some people do. That's a valid reason. 'I heard lab diamonds aren't real' is not."

### 3 Carat D-VVS2 Lab Grown Diamond Price

D-VVS2 in lab falls between our D-VVS1 [$7,000](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29116878?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) and D-FL [$11,770](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28637534?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) data points. In practice, 3ct D-VVS2 IGI Ideal stones run **$7,500–$9,500** depending on current inventory. Filter [Blue Nile lab-grown rounds](https://www.bluenile.com/round-cut-loose-diamonds?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) to 3ct, D color, VVS2 for today's pricing. VVS2 vs VVS1 face-up: identical.

